      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Etadanik Mistmorgue</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> An anti-regen spell would be deadly and probably overpowered for raiding and soloing.  Normal, non-uber mobs regen at the speed of a snail during combat - it's barely noticeable, and really means little in the greater scheme of things.  A mob out of combat regens at ridiculous speeds - mobs could regen 10k+ hp in under 2 minutes from what I observed.</P><P>Why this would overpower soloing:</P><P>Anti-regen a mob.  Put as many DoTs as you can on the mob.  FD.  After DoTs fade, repeat.  You can kill almost anything this way.</P><P>Why it would overpower raiding:</P><P>Zerging.  Anti-regen a mob and bind everyone nearby.  Zerg it and die.  Since the mob's regenning at a very low speed, you can then buff up and zerg again, over and over, till the mob is dead.  No skill required, really.</P><P>Now, assuming that both of these could be worked around, the only use I'd see for this spell would then be on ubers who regen really fast during the fight.  That would make this spell handy - except it doesn't make necros stack at all.  You only need ONE necro to anti-regen a mob.  Thus, I don't think it'd make us generally more desirable on raids at all.  It'd just make having one or two necros mandatory, which most guilds already do.</P><P>Just something to think about.  I think the heart of this post is at the right place, but there are difficulties involved with implementing such a spell, and whether it'd truly solve our problems.</P><P>But say this anti-regen was to go in, what if we made it so the spell lasts for 30 seconds, but has a recast time of 5 mins? That'd mean that in order to keep the mob perma-anti-regenned, it'd take 10 necros, which means a raid could arguably have up to 10 necros and still be operating at maximum efficiency (assuming DoT stacking goes in), and would make necros better over all.</P><P>Personally, there is a feature in DAOC that really would do EQ a lot of good - the idea of "focus" spells.  One caster has to relegate his entire mana pool and concentration just to keep a spell in effect.  This feature could be used to implement powerful, otherwise unbalancing spells.  Instead of one shaman slowing a pull of 5-6 or one enchanter mezzing a whole crowd, it'd make multiple shamans and multiple enchanters stack.  What if a shaman can only keep one mob slowed or an enchanter one mob mezzed? What if this feature was implemented on a level spread, so in exp groups enchanters/shamans can still reliably slow/mezz 5-6 mobs, but on raids it'd be impossible? Something to think about.</P><P><BR>Etadanik the Redeemed</font></td>
      </tr>
